**Elasticsearch version** (`bin/elasticsearch --version`):
7.15 (and probably earlier)
**Description of the problem including expected versus actual behavior**:
Significant terms is ignoring the background filter when one index has NO documents containing the term value.

**Steps to reproduce**:
Here are a long set of steps to reproduce

```
PUT repeat-test-1
{
  "mappings": {
    "properties": {
      "field1": {
        "type": "keyword"
      },
      "field2": {
        "type": "keyword"
      },
      "field3": {
        "type": "keyword"
      }
    }
  }
}

PUT repeat-test-2
{
  "mappings": {
    "properties": {
      "field1": {
        "type": "keyword"
      },
      "field2": {
        "type": "keyword"
      },
      "field3": {
        "type": "keyword"
      }
    }
  }
}

POST repeat-test-1/_bulk?refresh=true
{ "index" : {} }
{ "field1" : "failed", "field2": "frontend-node", "field3": "foo" }
{ "index" : {} }
{ "field1" : "failed", "field2": "frontend-node", "field3": "bar" }
{ "index" : {} }
{ "field1" : "failed", "field2": "frontend-node", "field3": "bar" }
{ "index" : {} }
{ "field1" : "success", "field2": "frontend-node", "field3": "bar" }
{ "index" : {} }
{ "field1" : "success", "field2": "frontend-node", "field3": "bar" }
{ "index" : {} }

POST repeat-test-2/_bulk?refresh=true
{ "index" : {} }
{ "field1" : "success", "field2": "java-node" }
{ "index" : {} }
{ "field1" : "success", "field2": "java-node" }
{ "index" : {} }
{ "field1" : "success", "field2": "java-node" }
{ "index" : {} }


GET repeat-test*/_search?track_total_hits=true&size=0
{
  "query": {
    "bool": {
      "filter": [
        {
          "term": {
            "field2": "frontend-node"
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  },
  "aggs": {
    "sig_term": {
      "significant_terms": {
        "field": "field3",
        "background_filter": {
          "bool": {
            "filter": [
              {
                "term": {
                  "field2": "frontend-node"
                }
              }
            ]
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

With the background filter, one expects the background count to be only `5` docs

But, it responds with:
```
"aggregations" : {
    "sig_term" : {
      "doc_count" : 5,
      "bg_count" : 8,
      "buckets" : [
        {
          "key" : "bar",
          "doc_count" : 4,
          "score" : 0.4800000000000001,
          "bg_count" : 4
        }
      ]
    }
  }
```
` "bg_count" : 8,`

Which means the 3 docs that don't match the filter were matched. 

Seems like a bad optimization as those docs also don't contain the term field `field3`

**Elasticsearch version** 7.14



**Description of the problem including expected versus actual behavior**:

### Setup
```
DELETE test
PUT test 
{
    "mappings": {
      "runtime": {
          "scripted_field": {
            "type": "keyword",
            "script": {
              "source": "for (v in doc['s.keyword']) {emit(v);}"
            }
          }
        },      
        "properties": {
            "s": {
                "type": "text",
                "fields": {
                    "keyword": {
                        "type": "keyword"
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
POST test/_doc/1
{
  "s": "lower"
}
```
### Example wildcard query that works
```
POST test/_search
{
  "query": {"wildcard": {"scripted_field": {"value": "*lower*"}}}
}
```

### Equivalent query_string wildcard query that fails
```
POST test/_search
{
  "query": {"query_string": {"default_field": "scripted_field", "query": "*lower*"}}
}
```
Failure is:
```
{
  "error" : {
    "root_cause" : [
      {
        "type" : "query_shard_exception",
        "reason" : "Can only use wildcard queries on keyword, text and wildcard fields - not on [scripted_field] which is of type [keyword]",
        "index_uuid" : "I_5QMeoNQD2SGqymVeyWaA",
        "index" : "test"
      }
    ],
    "type" : "search_phase_execution_exception",
    "reason" : "all shards failed",
    "phase" : "query",
    "grouped" : true,
    "failed_shards" : [
      {
        "shard" : 0,
        "index" : "test",
        "node" : "r3PXuCkJSuGBUacEV3FmIA",
        "reason" : {
          "type" : "query_shard_exception",
          "reason" : "Can only use wildcard queries on keyword, text and wildcard fields - not on [scripted_field] which is of type [keyword]",
          "index_uuid" : "I_5QMeoNQD2SGqymVeyWaA",
          "index" : "test"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "status" : 400
}
```

In a recent `master` (707dd497e489bb6917dc3d0bd58928ce13a33927) I saw a snapshot stress test trip the `Found shard snapshot waiting to be assigned` exception. The problematic shard was `[index-1][1]` and the assertion tripped at the cluster state transition which finalised a snapshot with a future clone queued up. The previous state of this shard was like this:

    snapshot:
    {
      "index": {
        "index_name": "index-1",
        "index_uuid": "kigpd8yeTZm5R6PHbZKpww"
      },
      "shard": 1,
      "state": "FAILED",
      "generation": "CcvNa4iURmCdg0YDvwIM9w",
      "node": "PgoVP627RAqZnA5y4ZQeDQ",
      "reason": "node shutdown"
    },

    clone:
    {
      "index": {
        "name": "index-1",
        "id": "3cG2OCEuSB2MINCVHFxI4g"
      },
      "shard": 1,
      "state": "QUEUED",
      "generation": null,
      "node": null
    }

The finalisation removed the first entry, leaving the dangling `QUEUED` clone. FWIW the shard was in yellow health at the time, although as a clone we should be able to proceed even if it were red.

Full test output in case it helps: [testoutput-1630475019.tar.gz](https://github.com/elastic/elasticsearch/files/7088887/testoutput-1630475019.tar.gz)

